So i'll close this one out, I discovered what the issue was and it was not to do with Alpine linux. 

We have a process that clears out any mention of source maps along with a few other cleanup steps.     
The script we've been using lo locate and sanitize looks for mentions of `//# sourceMappingURL=*.map` in the outputted JS files. 

It would seem that in the latest versions of Next the SourceMap declaration is on the same line as the closing bracket, where as previously it was on a new line.   The script was removing the line which in turn broke the closing bracket.

So, in next 12 it looks like 
```
    };
} //# sourceMappingURL=head-manager.js.map
```

in next 11 it was 

```
    };
} 
//# sourceMappingURL=head-manager.js.map
```

We've fixed this up and its now building properly.    Our fault, but thought it was worth reporting just incase.

I'm not entirely sure on all the accounts, but here's what I can share.

We were able to override the transform by providing the exact same key for the transformers that next is using when calling swc.  Inside the next/jest file, they have a spread operator on the transforms so they can be extended, but if you give it the exact same key they're using, you can just override their key.

in the `jest.config.js` file: (even if you're not using ts/tsx, you still need the string to match)
```
+  transform: {
+    '^.+\\.(js|jsx|ts|tsx)$': "ts-jest"
+  },
```

You could probably do something similar by providing `babel-jest` to that argument instead of `ts-jest`.

Then you can add the globals key to the jest config, and add any babel configuration options in there instead of having a `.babelrc` file.  I did this to override some of the tsconfig options.

```
+  globals: {
+    'ts-jest': {
+      tsconfig: {
+        jsx: "react-jsx"
+      }
+    }
+  }
```

So for you, you would have a `jest-babel` key there, and then either pass a custom babelrc location with (again, I think) `babelrcFile: ".bablerc.test"`, or just have your babel options right in the config.

*Note: I didn't test any of this with babel, I'm just extrapolating from how it works with ts-jest and the jest.config.js globals options*


*__Edit:__* FWIW you don't even have to use typescript at all to have the typescript compiler compile your jsx because all valid javascript is valid typescript.  So you could use the typescript compiler to just compile the jsx for babel.  Maybe thats overkill, IDK.

Thank you for the pointers @sorahn ! With the help of that and with some luck because it was my first reattempt to work around the problem, I only added the `transform` block shown shown here: https://nextjs.org/docs/testing#setting-up-jest-with-babel and that was all was needed to work around the issue! My `jest.config.js` now looks like this:

```js
const nextJest = require("next/jest");

const createJestConfig = nextJest({
  // Provide the path to your Next.js app to load next.config.js and .env files in your test environment
  dir: "./",
});

// Add any custom config to be passed to Jest
const customJestConfig = {
  setupFilesAfterEnv: ["<rootDir>/jest.setup.js"],
  // if using TypeScript with a baseUrl set to the root directory then you need the below for alias' to work
  moduleDirectories: ["node_modules", "<rootDir>/"],
  transform: {
    // Use babel-jest to transpile tests with the next/babel preset
    // https://jestjs.io/docs/configuration#transform-objectstring-pathtotransformer--pathtotransformer-object
    "^.+\\.(js|jsx|ts|tsx)$": ["babel-jest", { presets: ["next/babel"] }],
  },
  testEnvironment: "jest-environment-jsdom",
};

// createJestConfig is exported this way to ensure that next/jest can load the Next.js config which is async
module.exports = createJestConfig(customJestConfig);
```

Should Next.js documentation and `with-jest` example be updated to reflect this work around and maybe help save some other beginners headaches? ;)

