In general something like this can happen. Here is a general explanation when this can happen:

Each module will be placed in the module cache at runtime where it can be received by any importing module. It's not possible to load a module twice, as this would duplicate state and identities in that module, which cause weird effects. So webpack ensures that it's only loaded once. As example we assume that module X and module Y import module M. Both will get the same instance of M.
Now we add unused export elimination to the game. Let's assume module X uses only export A of module M and module Y used only export B of module M. As both must receive the same instance of M, we need generate a version of M that includes both exports A and B.
This is true in general, even if X and Y are in different chunk resp loaded on demand. We always have to prepare for the case where X and Y are loaded together and both need to share the same instance of M. So it always need to have both exports A and B.

That's what's happening here too. `domMax` and `m` are transitively depend on the same module `framer-motion/dist/es/projection/node/create-projection-node.mjs`. `domMax` uses the export `createProjectionNode` while `m` is not using it. But because `domMax` can eventually be loaded together with `m` we need to prepare for that case and include `createProjectionNode` in the only existing version of `create-projection-node.mjs`. Unfortunally `create-projection-node.mjs` is already referenced by `m` at startup, so it need to be included in `_app` and can't placed in the on demand chunk with `domMax`.
Unfortunally using `createProjectionNode` makes a huge difference in the same of the module, since a lot (side-effect-free) imports are only used within that export. So when it's not used a large part of the import tree can be skipped.

I debugged that with this next.config.js:

``` js
const path = require('path');
module.exports = {
  webpack(config) {
    config.optimization.minimize = false;
    config.optimization.concatenateModules = false;
    config.output.pathinfo = 'verbose';
    return config;
  },
};
```

This enables some verbose comments about used and unused exports in the generated file. It also disables minimizing and concatenation to make these comments readable per module.

Here is the relevant part of the diff between importing `domMax` and not importing it in the on demand chunk:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1365881/177497709-66b5d4fc-82d7-4dcf-a9c9-be5a59a5055d.png)

Usually this can be fixed by placing these conflicting exports into separate files. e. g. here `globalProjectionState` could be moved into a separate file, which would fix the problem in that case. (Not sure if there are more cases in that scenario, I stopped looking for them after I found the first one)

