You ask a good question about how many other plugins support config functions. I took a quick look at the source for [next-plugin-preact](https://github.com/preactjs/next-plugin-preact/blob/master/packages/next-plugin-preact/index.js), [@next/bundle-analyzer](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/packages/next-bundle-analyzer/index.js), and the deprecated [next-mdx-enhanced](https://github.com/hashicorp/next-mdx-enhanced/blob/main/index.js). It looks like all of them expect a config object, and none of them work with config functions.

These plugins often get chained together:

```js
const withPreact = require('next-plugin-preact');
const withMDX = require("@next/mdx")();

module.exports = withPreact(withMDX({
    /* regular next.js config options here */
}));
```

Allowing `withMDX()` to accept a function would actually break `withPreact()` in the example above: `withMDX()` would need to return a function in order for it to handle a function, and `withPreact()` only handles object configs. It's probably best not to introduce a change that could break compatibility somewhere else.

