Hi, NextAuth.js maintainer here, this is not a bug in Next.js (or NextAuth.js), let me explain:

```js
MyApp.getInitialProps = async (appContext: AppContext): Promise<AppInitialProps & CustomProps> => {
  const appProps = await App.getInitialProps(appContext);

  const session = (await getSession(appContext.ctx)) as Session;
  return { ...appProps, session };
};
```

This code together with `getStaticProps` on your `index` page has a few issues.

You instruct Next.js to invoke a session call that together with the getStaticProps call will generate a static version of the site, including your credentials. (You can even observe this at build-time when a `[next-auth][error][CLIENT_FETCH_ERROR]` error will show up in your logs)

To mitigate the issue, you have a few options:

1. NextAuth.js recently introduced Middleware. Using that, you can lock down your whole site with a single line:
```js
export { default } from "next-auth/middleware"
```

See the [NextAuth.js Middleware documentation](https://next-auth.js.org/configuration/nextjs#middleware) for more information.

2. use `getServerSideProps`: Fetching the user data _must_ happen dynamically, to avoid caching sensitive information. Instead of `getInitialProps` + `getStaticSideProps`, you can simply add the following to your desired pages:
```js
export async function getServerSideProps(ctx) {
  return {
    props: { session: await getSession(ctx)}
  }
}
```
If you think it's tedious to add this to several pages, you can define this function in a shared location and add only this to the pages:

```js
export { getServerSideProps } from "shared"
```

NOTE: The only gain with using getServerSideProps is to avoid a flash of content. With a nice loading UI, this can be mitigated, preserving the static nature of your site, while waiting for the user to be authenticated.

I was going to suggest a third solution, but it is actually worse than not trying to pass the session at all. If you add a `typeof window` check in your `getInitialProps` when fetching the session, you could avoid caching the credentials. The downside is that this logic will run on every client-side page transition, re-fetching the session again and again. If `SessionProvider` does not receive an initial `session` as a prop, it will simply go and fetch it itself, and use this cached version on navigation. (Resulting in a single call instead of one per page navigation.). To keep a session "alive" when you might have a short session lifetime, you could use [session polling](https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/client#refetch-interval) instead. So this option makes it kind of clear that `getInitialProps` is not really suited for authentication.

You can find similar suggestions in the official Next.js documentation on authentication: https://nextjs.org/docs/authentication#authenticating-statically-generated-pages

