That's currently a limitation of webpack. Improving that would require some move advanced code transformation/optimizations which can't be easily implemented.

The reason behind this is that there can only be a single variant of the module `strings.ts` in all pages, since multiple pages can be loaded together at runtime (you can navigate from page `test` to `test2` at runtime on client side, which will load both).

It's not possible to duplicate a module and tree shake it in different ways when they can be potentially loaded at the same time. A module could potentially include state (even while that is not the case here) which would be illegal to duplicate.

There are some workarounds to that.

The easiest way is to put each string in a separate file.

``` js
// string1.ts
export const STRING1 = "string1";

// string2.ts
export const STRING2 = "string2";

// pages/test.tsx
import { STRING1 } from '../string1';
...

// pages/test2.tsx
import { STRING2 } from '../string2';
```

Another way it to use reexports for a side-effect-free flagged file.

``` js
// string1.ts
export const STRING1 = "string1";

// string2.ts
export const STRING2 = "string2";

// strings.ts - shared utility file
export { STRING1 } from "./string1.ts";
export { STRING2 } from "./string2.ts";

// package.json
{
  "sideEffects": false
}

// pages/test.tsx
import { STRING1 } from '../strings';
...

// pages/test2.tsx
import { STRING2 } from '../strings';
```

