Hello @JackCA!

This issue will be fixed as port of the upcoming changes in middleware.
Here is a working example with 12.1.7-canary.41, that will no trigger a full page reload when clicking on the link:

```js
// file /middleware.js
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server'

export default function middleware(req) {
  if (req.nextUrl.pathname === '/') {
    return NextResponse.next()
  }
  const url = req.nextUrl.clone()
  url.pathname = `/foo${url.pathname}`
  return NextResponse.rewrite(url)
}

export const config = {
  matcher: ['/', '/:path'],
}
```

(I opened a [PR](https://github.com/JackCA/next-broken-middleware/pull/1) to your reproduction repository, thanks for it!)

This "new" middleware applies new conventions you may not be aware of: they are part of the latest changes:
- middleware have no leading _ character
- no more nested middleware: a single file in the root folder
- optional route matching (`config.matcher` exported property, works the same as [next.config redirects or headers](https://nextjs.org/docs/api-reference/next.config.js/redirects#path-matching))

Please note that all changes will be fully documented (there's already a migration guide [here](https://nextjs.org/docs/messages/middleware-upgrade-guide)) for the next stable release.
